  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense and is subject to legal prosecution in most jurisdictions, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This activity undermines the integrity of financial systems and is often associated with organized crime, corruption, and other illegal activities.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** (\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u53cd\u6d17\u94b1\u6cd5) and related regulations. The law requires financial institutions and certain non-financial entities to establish robust anti-money laundering measures, including customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions. Violators can face severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nThe Chinese government has been actively strengthening its anti-money laundering efforts in recent years, aligning with international standards and cooperating with global financial institutions to combat this crime. If you have any specific questions or need further details, feel free to ask!",
